[1] Brazil (Sao Paulo)
Date: 19 Jun 2007
Source: Jornal da Manha [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.jornaldamanha.com/visualizar.php?not=19052>

Yesterday [18 Jun 2007] Municipal Epidemiological
Surveillance totaled the number of dengue cases
since the start of last week [10 Jun 2007]. From
the data provided, the [municipal] health units
recorded an additional 15 victims [clinically
diagnosed as dengue] plus the 6 that had
laboratory diagnosis by the Adolfo Lutz Institute.
These data bring to a total of 1809 cases of this
disease this year [2007]. In the first days of
the month [Jun 2007] 21 [cases] were registered,
the same number [of cases] as were announced
yesterday.
In the last week of May [2007] there were 61
cases, in the previous [week] 75, and before that
84 and 153. The progressive decline in the
numbers of cases indicate that the epidemic is
easing and may be drawing to an end.
Of the total cases up until the present, 972 were
laboratory diagnosed (serology) and 837
clinically by physicians, based on symptoms.
Despite the dry season, which does not favor the
accumulation of water, essential for the
proliferation of the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_,
the vector of dengue [virus], the population must
remain on alert.
"As temperatures go higher, that is positive for
_Aedes_ breeding. As people permit water to
accumulate, the numbers of dengue cases diagnosed
will continue," affirmed the coordinator of the
Municipal Secretariat of Health, Danilo Bigeschi.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There is an old saying that characterizes
persons [living in] poverty: "they sell their
lunch in order to buy dinner." This is how public
health [addresses] dengue control, counting
case-by-case and the accompanying trends as
though there were a stock market. One case more
or one less does not make a difference -- what is
important is that every 3 or 4 years we will live
through another [dengue] epidemic. - Mod.LJS,
trans. from Portuguese Mods.TY/JW]
[It is extraordinarily difficult to get the
public to continue to eliminate _Aedes aegypti_
breeding sites long after the dengue epidemic
ends, to prevent recurrence of dengue virus
transmission and a new outbreak.
Marilia is located in the western sector of
greater Sao Paulo, Brazil. A map of Marilia can
be accessed at:
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/BR/27/Marilia.html>. - Mod.TY]
