[2] Guyana: suspected
Date: 22 Jun 2007
Source: Stabroek News [edited]
<http://www.stabroeknews.com/index.pl/article_general_news?id=56522970>

Cases of dengue fever have been reported in the
Lethem area, but while authorities are seeing
many persons with signs and symptoms they have no
kits to test them, Acting Regional Health Officer
(RHO) Eugene Xavier says.
When contacted, Xavier confirmed that there was a
number of cases. He said up to last week Friday
[15 Jun 2007] they had kits and they had
confirmed some 11 cases, but the kits have run
out. Since then, they have seen a number of
persons with signs and symptoms who have come up
negative for malaria when tested. He said this
means that more than likely, those persons have
dengue fever, but there is no way to prove this.
Contact was made with Director of Disease Control
Services, Dr. Shamdeo Persaud, who told Stabroek
News that he had not heard any such reports. He
said usually the ministry would contact RHOs and
collect data on a weekly basis and it had not
received any such reports. He expressed surprise
that officials could say definitively that it was
dengue fever, since, according to him,
confirmatory tests for dengue had to be done by
the Caribbean Epidemiology Centre (CAREC).
He said the kits to which Xavier referred were
used to test for antibodies. If a person was
exposed to any of the viruses that cause dengue
fever previously, the antibody would show up. As
a result one should wait until the definitive
test was done by CAREC to diagnose dengue.
Persaud explained that if his department was
informed it would have advised the region's
officials on vector control measures since there
was no specific medication for treating dengue
fever. The public would be advised to cover their
water supply since the _Aedes_ mosquito, which
transmits the disease, thrives in fresh water.
Also, the public would be advised to use insect
repellent and mosquito nets to minimize being
bitten by mosquitoes. Dr. Persaud had promised to
contact the regional officials and had advised
this reporter to call him back but when calls
were placed to his office he was not there.
According to Xavier, no one was hospitalised at
the moment, but the situation was worrying. He
said persons were treated for some of the
symptoms and since most of them live in Lethem
they were being monitored. He said that the
neighbouring Brazilian town, Bon Fim, did not
have a dengue outbreak. On Wednesday [20 Jun
2007] he met the town's Chamber of Commerce head
who informed that while there were cases of
malaria there was no dengue fever. The
authorities there were said to be in the process
of fogging the area. The acting RHO expressed the
need to have the Lethem area fogged as well.
[Byline: Oluatoyin Alleyne]
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett
[ProMED requests additional information on this
suspected dengue outbreak as it becomes
available. A diagnosis based on serology done on
single samples not involving IgG capture is not
adequate to establish dengue virus etiology of
these suspected cases. Flaviviruses, the family
to which dengue virus belongs, are notoriously
cross-reactive in serological tests.
A map of Guyana can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/guyana.gif>. - Mod.TY]
