[4] India (Kerala)
Date: 21 Jun 2007
Source: The Hindu [edited]
<http://www.hindu.com/2007/06/21/stories/2007062158280300.htm>

Thiruvananthapuram: More dengue cases have been
reported in the Thiruvananthapuram district with
the laboratory confirmation of 8 serum samples
that had been collected earlier. On Wednesday [20
Jun 2007] 4 fever cases reported are also
suspected to be dengue.
This apart, one case of imported malaria and 31
fever cases suspected to be chikungunya were also
reported from the district on Wednesday [20 Jun
2007]. So far, 532 suspected cases of chikungunya
and 98 confirmed cases of dengue have been
reported in the district this year [2007]. The
dengue cases, which had been on a low till May
[2007], went up following pre-monsoon showers.
Dengue has been endemic in the district for quite
a few years. Over 60 percent of the total dengue
case load in the State is being reported from
Thiruvananthapuram since the past 3 or 4 years
now. Of the 8 confirmed cases of dengue, 5 are of
children under treatment at SAT hospital.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett
[It is not clear how the dengue and chikungunya
cases are being differentiated clinically, in the
absence of laboratory tests.
A map of Kerala, India, can be accessed at:
<http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/kerala/kerala.htm>. - Mod.TY]
