[5] Singapore
Date: 19 Jun 2007
Source: Estadao [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.estadao.com.br:80/ciencia/noticias/2007/jun/19/234.htm>

The number of dengue cases in Singapore has
reached epidemic levels for the 1st time since an
outbreak of the disease infected thousands in the
city-state in 2006, as shown by government
statistics. During the past week [week of 10 Jun
2007] 401 cases were recorded, which exceeds the
level for an epidemic as defined by the local
administration.
The current outbreak has caused 2 deaths, evoking
local leader's memories of the 2005 epidemic, in
which 25 people died and thousands of persons
were infected in a population of 4.5 million
inhabitants.
Health authorities are checking habitations,
looking for breeding sites of the mosquito vector.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Singapore was an example of dengue control for
the world. Control of dengue is an inglorious and
difficult task. - Mod.LJS]
[A map of Singapore can be accessed at:
<http://www.hot-maps.de/asia/singapore/singapore/homeen.html> - Mod. TY]
